<subSubSection pageNumber="507" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="507">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="507">Note:</emphasis>
Grierson (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="507">Ceylon J. Sci., Biol. Sci.</emphasis>
11: 15. 1974) argued that 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
apparent inclusion of 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Artemisia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="minima">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="507">Artemisia minima</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L (1753) in the protologue was a bibliographic confusion resulting from proof copies of 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Burman’s">Burman's</normalizedToken>
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="507">Fl. Indica.</emphasis>
He argued that Linnaeus corrected this later (in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="507">Mant. Pl. Alt</emphasis>
.: 572. 1771), and that 
<taxonomicName authority="L." authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Epaltes" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="divaricata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="507">E. divaricata</emphasis>
L.
</taxonomicName>
is not illegitimate.
</paragraph>
